Introduction¶

Coffee is an important beverage in the global economy. It is made from the seeds of the coffee plant, which are called coffee beans. Coffee plants require a certain temperature to grow and thrive. These temperatures are found mainly in South America, primarily Brazil who is responsible for a third of the world's coffee output. This is due to the rich soils and tropical climate in the country. About 70% of the coffee produced in Brazil is the Arabica coffee, from the coffea arabica plant, while the remaining is roughly made up of Robusta coffee, from the coffea canephora plant. Arabica is known to be more sugary, flavory with the perfect amount of caffeine, and is very likely the coffee you had this very morning. As caffeine and subsequently coffee consumption have grown in the last decades, the investment of coffee industries, both foreign and domestic, into these farms have risen.

The coffea arabica plant is requires an ideal temperature of 18 - 22 $^{\circ}$C, and can tolerate mean annual temperatures of 24 $^{\circ}$C. A high sensitivity to temperature and precipitation conditions renders arabica coffee production susceptible to increasing temperatures. With temperatures expected to rise globally, we're interested in studying the effects of these rising temperatures on coffee production, whether it's significant, if yes, exactly when will the production decline, etc. As coffee companies heavily invest and rely on these farms for their revenue, any such effects will have a direct implication in their business strategy and alter its dynamics.

Our study region consists of two states in Brazil - Minas Gerais and Rio Grande Do Sul. The state of Minas Gerais accounts nearly 50% of the country's coffee production, and is the main hub for Brazil's Arabica production (about 75% of the state's coffee output is arabica). Rio Grande Do Sul is a southern state with developing agriculture and rich lands. We're interested in the temperature forecasts of these regions.

Modelling¶

We want to develop a model that fits into our time series data. To do this, we have to check if the time series is stationary, and if not, we must stationarize it as all standard time series models rely on this feature.

Stationarity¶

If we consider the significance level to be 0.05 then, for the above p-value < 0.05 result, we can say that the series is stationary.

SARIMA Model¶

We decided to use a seasonal ARIMA (SARIMA) model for fitting our time series. We chose 1856 months of time series data for our training set and the remaining (240) for the test set.

In [16]:
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score
import statsmodels.api as sm

# Defining a root mean-squared error function
rmse = lambda x, y: np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(x,y))
test_size = 240
train_size = len(mg) - test_size
trainset = mg[['AverageTemperature']][:-test_size].copy()
testset = mg[['AverageTemperature']][-test_size:].copy()
In [65]:
# We found these orders to be the best fit for the data
p, d, q = (1, 1, 0)
P, D, Q, S = (1, 1, 2, 12)
sarima = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(trainset, order=(p, d, q), seasonal_order=(P, D, Q, S),
                                    simple_differencing=0, enforce_stationarity=True, enforce_invertibility=False)
mfit = sarima.fit()  

testpred = mfit.forecast(test_size) 
testpred.index = testset.index

RSS = np.sqrt(sum(testpred.values-testset.values.reshape(-1))**2)/test_size
print(f'Root Squared Error of SARIMAX model(p,d,q)(p,d,q,s):' ,(p, d, q),(P, D, Q, S),':', round(RSS, 3),"\n")
print(mfit.summary())

Stacked LSTM Model (Deep Learning)¶

Deep Learning models can learn complex patterns and features. In particular, LSTMs, a variant of RNNs, are good at time series modelling as they can account for the sequential nature of a time series. We decided to use a stacked LSTM model, feeding in the target, lagged features and a time dummy variable, in order to predict against the target, which is the average temperature. The good thing about deep learning models is that we don't need to provide any terms for stationarity or seasonality, it automatically detects the complex patterns in the data.

# Function to generate sequence data i.e. a sliding window
def sliding_windows(data, seq_length):
    x, y = [], []
    for i in range(len(data)-seq_length):
        x_ = data[i:i + seq_length]
        y_ = data[i + seq_length]
        x.append(x_)
        y.append(y_)

    return np.array(x),np.array(y)
In [111]:
# LSTMs are sensitive to the input range, and learns best when there's a standard scaling of data
sc = MinMaxScaler()
sc_d = MinMaxScaler()


seq_length = 24 # Sequence length of 24 months

scdata_avg = sc.fit_transform(deepmg[['AverageTemperature']])
scdata_l3 = sc.transform(deepmg[['lag 3']])
scdata_l6 = sc.transform(deepmg[['lag 6']])
scdata_l9 = sc.transform(deepmg[['lag 9']])
scdata_d = sc_d.fit_transform(deepmg[['dummy']])

x_avg, y_avg = sliding_windows(scdata_avg, seq_length)
x_lag3, y_lag3 = sliding_windows(scdata_l3, seq_length)
x_lag6, y_lag6 = sliding_windows(scdata_l6, seq_length)
x_lag9, y_lag9 = sliding_windows(scdata_l9, seq_length)

x_d, y_d = sliding_windows(scdata_d, seq_length)


X_train_mg = np.concatenate((x_avg, x_d, x_lag3, x_lag6, x_lag9), axis=2)
y_train_mg = y_avg.reshape(-1,1)
print(X_train_mg.shape, y_train_mg.shape)

(2063, 24, 5) (2063, 1)

We decided to train the stacked LSTM model on the entire dataset, as we want the model to learn even on the last few years of data (which we would have usually excluded to include in the test set, thereby leading to the model having no information on it)

In [24]:
n_features = 5

model = Sequential()
model.add(LSTM(128, activation='relu',return_sequences=True, input_shape=(seq_length, n_features)))
model.add(LSTM(64, activation='relu', return_sequences=False))
model.add(Dense(32))
model.add(Dense(1))
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse')

model.fit(X_train_mg, y_train_mg, epochs=100, verbose=1)

Predicting the Future with Deep Learning¶

Using our trained LSTM model, we will now predict the future temperatures (uptil 2080). We could have also used the SARIMA model results to forecast the future temperatures, but we chose the Deep learning model.

In [113]:
import datetime
import monthdelta

fc_mg = deepmg[-seq_length:].copy()
j = fc_mg[-seq_length:]['dummy'][-1]
for i in range(67*12+4):
    inp1 = sc.transform(fc_mg[-seq_length:].values[:, 0].reshape(-1,1).astype(np.float32))
    inp2 = sc.transform(fc_mg[-seq_length:].values[:, 1].reshape(-1,1).astype(np.float32))
    inp3 = sc.transform(fc_mg[-seq_length:].values[:, 2].reshape(-1,1).astype(np.float32))
    inp4 = sc.transform(fc_mg[-seq_length:].values[:, 3].reshape(-1,1).astype(np.float32))
    td = sc_d.transform(fc_mg[-seq_length:].values[:, 4].reshape(-1,1).astype(np.float32))

    
    
    inp = np.stack((inp1, td, inp2, inp3, inp4), axis=2).reshape(1, -1, n_features)
    o = model.predict(inp)
    o = sc.inverse_transform(o)
    j = j+1
    fc_mg.loc[fc_mg.index[-1] + monthdelta.monthdelta(1)] = [o.squeeze(), 
                                                     fc_mg['AverageTemperature'][-3], 
                                                     fc_mg['AverageTemperature'][-6], 
                                                     fc_mg['AverageTemperature'][-9],
                                                     j]

Modelling¶

The stacked LSTM model gave us good results for the temperature data previously. We skipped the SARIMA model for Rio Grande Do Sul, and directly used a deep learning model for prediction. We don't need to analyse the stationarity or autocorrelations of the time series this time, as we're using a deep learning model.

sc = MinMaxScaler()

seq_length = 24 # Sequence length of 24 months

Conclusion¶

Our analysis suggests that there will be an impact on Arabica coffee production in Minas Gerais. The mean annual temperature is expected to exceed 24 $^\circ$C in 2065, beyond which Arabica production will reduce, as the lands become unsuitable for growing the plant. If other factors such as precipitation and probability of natural disasters are taken into account, this number may even be lower. The average yearly increase in temperature in Minas Gerais is around 0.02 $^\circ$C, which could be dangerous as higher temperatures also aid the proliferation of pests.

However, the state of Rio Grande Do Sul has rich agricultural land, and is at fairly low climate risk. The average temperatures is expected to reach only around 20.5 $^\circ$C in 2065, which is perfect for Arabica coffee production. The average yearly increase in temperature is only 0.014 $^\circ$C. Coffee businesses could consider investing in developing agricultural infrastructure for arabica production in this state, switching over from their investments in Minas Gerais.

Another possible solution could be investing in Robusta coffee production in Minas Gerais. Robusta , while not as popular, is more robust to climate change and pests, requiring about 24 - 30 $^\circ$C. Continuing to invest in arabica production simply may not be sustainable in the long run in Minas Gerais.
